    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-28T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-28T11:00:00-05:00" n="323"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d323">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">662.1115/62: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-28T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 28, 1934—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 28—12:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>45. Referring to my cable of February 20, number 40, last sentence, leading
                    members of the Foreign Office in conversation refer to wider market in the
                    United States as the outstanding opportunity to improve a foreign trade
                    situation which threatens to become catastrophe. For this purpose trade mission
                    to the United States is to be headed by Posse, State Secretary of Economics, as
                    the strongest available man. I was asked whether 16th March would be convenient
                    approximate date for mission to land in the United States. Please telegraph
                    immediately in case date inconvenient.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodd</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
